    <title>Combined summary - Change to multiple executables?</title>
    <updated>2023-06-04T18:15:08.426122+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2011-August/000328.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>In August 2011, Bitcoin developers discussed various proposals for changes in the cryptocurrency's protocol. One of the significant proposals was to split the mainline client into separate executables to simplify the main functions and prevent the UI from doubling as a daemon. However, there were concerns about users who run the UI and switch to RPC calls to inspect details, and whether this usage pattern is common. Separating the daemon from the UI would provide more flexibility for remote control of the Bitcoin daemon and potentially simplify future development efforts.The email thread also discussed the reluctance of new developers to join the project due to their suggestions being shot down, with some members suggesting that the community needs to become more flexible and open to change or risk losing developers. Developers are urged to adequately reflect the needs of the userbase, and backward compatibility is emphasized as an essential consideration when making any changes to the protocol. Breaking backward compatibility means breaking people's access to their own money, so any proposed changes must be made with caution to avoid negative consequences. Gavin Andresen argued that the project needs more testers and people helping to fix bugs and scalability issues, rather than developers proposing new features. The email conversations also discussed various ideas related to Bitcoin, including backward compatibility issues and the negative reception of some ideas. Jeff Garzik argued that backward compatibility is essential since breaking it would mean breaking people's access to their money. Despite this, Andy suggested using a version number field combined with a complex process that allows nodes time to upgrade. Other ideas were to remove verack as it is unnecessary and may cause compatibility issues, querying miners for pending transactions, and requesting block bodies without headers to save traffic for a thin client upgrading.Overall, the discussions highlight the complexities involved in making changes to the Bitcoin protocol while ensuring security and stability. Backward compatibility and community involvement are emphasized as important considerations to ensure the continued success and growth of the project. The dev team believes that user feedback is essential in determining if a breaking change is necessary, and it should be done with caution to avoid negative consequences. Open source maintainers often say "no" more than they say "yes", and proposals should not be taken personally.</summary>
